    </node>
    <node id="Multi-Scale Training">
      <data key="d0">Multi-Scale Training</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Multi-scale training is a method in machine learning where images are rescaled individually by sampling scale parameter S from a range, enhancing model robustness to object size variability.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-c221c2172115966280bf240634f365bc</data>
      <data key="d4">Very_Deep_Convolutional_Networks_for_Large-Scale_Image_Recognition_content_list.json</data>
      <data key="d5">1774858955</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Scale S">
      <data key="d0">Scale S</data>
      <data key="d1">data</data>
      <data key="d2">Scale S refers to the scaling factor sampled from a specified range used to rescale training images in multi-scale training.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-c221c2172115966280bf240634f365bc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-734c10ac044155da7db3e75d71944bea</data>
      <data key="d4">Very_Deep_Convolutional_Networks_for_Large-Scale_Image_Recognition_content_list.json</data>
      <data key="d5">1774858955</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Range [S_min, S_max]">
      <data key="d0">Range [S_min, S_max]</data>
      <data key="d1">data</data>
      <data key="d2">The range [S_min, S_max] specifies the minimum and maximum bounds (e.g., 256 and 512) for sampling the scale S during training.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-c221c2172115966280bf240634f365bc</data>
      <data key="d4">Very_Deep_Convolutional_Networks_for_Large-Scale_Image_Recognition_content_list.json</data>
      <data key="d5">1774858956</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Object in Images">
      <data key="d0">Object in Images</data>
      <data key="d1">naturalobject</data>
      <data key="d2">Objects within images vary in size, influencing the necessity for scale augmentation during training.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-c221c2172115966280bf240634f365bc</data>
      <data key="d4">Very_Deep_Convolutional_Networks_for_Large-Scale_Image_Recognition_content_list.json</data>
      <data key="d5">1774858956</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Set of Object Sizes">
      <data key="d0">Set of Object Sizes</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">The set of object sizes within images influences the effectiveness of training methods such as multi-scale training.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-c221c2172115966280bf240634f365bc</data>
      <data key="d4">Very_Deep_Convolutional_Networks_for_Large-Scale_Image_Recognition_content_list.json</data>
      <data key="d5">1774858956</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Input Image">
      <data key="d0">Input Image</data>
      <data key="d1">naturalobject</data>
      <data key="d2">The input image is the data subjected to classification, resized to a predefined smallest side $Q$.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-734c10ac044155da7db3e75d71944bea</data>
      <data key="d4">Very_Deep_Convolutional_Networks_for_Large-Scale_Image_Recognition_content_list.json</data>
      <data key="d5">1774858956</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Scale Q">
      <data key="d0">Scale Q</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">The scale $Q$ is the predefined image size to which input images are isotropically rescaled before classification.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-734c10ac044155da7db3e75d71944bea&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-910b19d5d7e003782ec85519b01d0c2b</data>
      <data key="d4">Very_Deep_Convolutional_Networks_for_Large-Scale_Image_Recognition_content_list.json</data>
      <data key="d5">1774858956</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Training Scale S">
      <data key="d0">Training Scale S</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">The training scale $S$ is the size used during the training phase, which may differ from $Q$.&lt;SEP&gt;The scale S used during training of the ConvNet, which can be fixed or variable, influencing the range of testing scales.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-734c10ac044155da7db3e75d71944bea&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6368d2fa701e57fb8c2f2d07d4ed361f</data>
      <data key="d4">Very_Deep_Convolutional_Networks_for_Large-Scale_Image_Recognition_content_list.json</data>
      <data key="d5">1774858957</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Fully-Connected Layers">
      <data key="d0">Fully-Connected Layers</data>
      <data key="d1">method</data>
      <data key="d2">Fully-Connected (FC) layers are layers in a neural network with specified channel counts, following convolutional layers.&lt;SEP&gt;Fully-connected layers are converted into convolutional layers to facilitate dense application over images.&lt;SEP&gt;Fully-connected layers are a type of neural network layer that were fine-tuned in model D to improve performance.&lt;SEP&gt;A type of neural network layer that, when fine-tuned, results in better localization performance.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-734c10ac044155da7db3e75d71944bea&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-23eb0012359dac75ed79e6c991260f55&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9bd30b9c62f11080adc575b0dedc0a8f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-889051f3aa4e6a4f8a9d1d83c0a6b8d8</data>
      <data key="d4">Very_Deep_Convolutional_Networks_for_Large-Scale_Image_Recognition_content_list.json</data>
      <data key="d5">1774858957</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Convolutional Layers">
      <data key="d0">Convolutional Layers</data>
      <data key="d1">content</data>
      <data key="d2">Convolutional layers are a series of layered components in a neural network, with varying depths in different architectures.&lt;SEP&gt;Convolutional layers in ConvNets apply filters, such as 3x3 or 1x1, to extract features from input images.&lt;SEP&gt;Convolutional layers are specific neural network components that process spatial data, initialized with layers from configuration A.&lt;SEP&gt;Convolutional layers replace fully-connected layers in the adapted network architecture.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-734c10ac044155da7db3e75d71944bea&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-8a54d3c176db1485ff70ae6846b62da3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-23eb0012359dac75ed79e6c991260f55&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0ab6dde5b80886f30a7bb92c12b0d072</data>
      <data key="d4">Very_Deep_Convolutional_Networks_for_Large-Scale_Image_Recognition_content_list.json</data>
      <data key="d5">1774858957</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Class Score Map">
      <data key="d0">Class Score Map</data>
      <data key="d1">content</data>
      <data key="d2">A spatial map of class scores output by the network, with channels equal to the number of classes and variable resolution.&lt;SEP&gt;Class score maps are output from the classification ConvNet, used to rate bounding box predictions during the merging process.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-734c10ac044155da7db3e75d71944bea&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-fed433068f333767bf66e9a93a7e311c</data>
      <data key="d4">Very_Deep_Convolutional_Networks_for_Large-Scale_Image_Recognition_content_list.json</data>
      <data key="d5">1774858958</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Score Vector">
      <data key="d0">Score Vector</data>
      <data key="d1">content</data>
      <data key="d2">A fixed-size vector of class scores obtained by spatially averaging the class score map.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-734c10ac044155da7db3e75d71944bea</data>
      <data key="d4">Very_Deep_Convolutional_Networks_for_Large-Scale_Image_Recognition_content_list.json</data>
      <data key="d5">1774858958</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Test Set">
      <data key="d0">Test Set</data>
      <data key="d1">data</data>
      <data key="d2">The set of images augmented by horizontal flipping used to improve classification accuracy.&lt;SEP&gt;The test set is employed in experiments to assess the accuracy of image classification models and is submitted to official evaluation servers.&lt;SEP&gt;The test set results show configuration E achieving a top-5 error of 7.3%.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-734c10ac044155da7db3e75d71944bea&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7bd4c026d1ee9227f8df517ef0dc9a7a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-cb0d159c3ed83612608daea64febc962</data>
      <data key="d4">Very_Deep_Convolutional_Networks_for_Large-Scale_Image_Recognition_content_list.json</data>
      <data key="d5">1774858958</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Softmax Posteriors">
      <data key="d0">Softmax Posteriors</data>
      <data key="d1">content</data>
      <data key="d2">Probability estimates of class membership for original and flipped images, averaged to finalize scores.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-734c10ac044155da7db3e75d71944bea</data>
      <data key="d4">Very_Deep_Convolutional_Networks_for_Large-Scale_Image_Recognition_content_list.json</data>
      <data key="d5">1774858958</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Sermanet et al.">
      <data key="d0">Sermanet et al.</data>
      <data key="d1">person</data>
      <data key="d2">Sermanet et al. are researchers who worked on improving ConvNet architectures, specifically on receptive window size and multi-scale training.&lt;SEP&gt;Sermanet et al. is a research group or authors associated with the method of applying the network densely over images.&lt;SEP&gt;Sermanet et al. (2014) is the researcher(s) associated with the development of OverFeat, an image localization method evaluated in the comparison.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-734c10ac044155da7db3e75d71944bea&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-47b4639bc17afbd91af6777585180e5b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-668a86d65078bf8021d84fd665b305f7</data>
      <data key="d4">Very_Deep_Convolutional_Networks_for_Large-Scale_Image_Recognition_content_list.json</data>
      <data key="d5">1774858958</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Training Scale">
      <data key="d0">Training Scale</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Training scale, also referred to as 'S', is the smallest side dimension of the scaled training image, influencing the crop and statistical representation.&lt;SEP&gt;Scale $S$ is a parameter in neural network training related to image content size and is explored via fixed and multiscale approaches.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-414840d58c9c17244c8e4774f512dc8f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a661234bc5d404231fbf23c25c0f103e</data>
      <data key="d4">Very_Deep_Convolutional_Networks_for_Large-Scale_Image_Recognition_content_list.json</data>
      <data key="d5">1774858958</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Single-Scale Training">
      <data key="d0">Single-Scale Training</data>
      <data key="d1">method</data>
      <data key="d2">An approach where the training uses a fixed scale $S$, maintaining consistent image size during training.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-414840d58c9c17244c8e4774f512dc8f</data>
      <data key="d4">Very_Deep_Convolutional_Networks_for_Large-Scale_Image_Recognition_content_list.json</data>
      <data key="d5">1774858958</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Multiscale Image Statistics">
      <data key="d0">Multiscale Image Statistics</data>
      <data key="d1">content</data>
      <data key="d2">Refers to the analysis and representation of images across multiple scales within the training process.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-414840d58c9c17244c8e4774f512dc8f</data>
      <data key="d4">Very_Deep_Convolutional_Networks_for_Large-Scale_Image_Recognition_content_list.json</data>
      <data key="d5">1774858958</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Model">
      <data key="d0">Model</data>
      <data key="d1">content</data>
      <data key="d2">A neural network trained with specific scales, such as $S = 256$ or $S = 384$, for task learning.&lt;SEP&gt;The model is a trained machine learning system designed to recognize objects across various scales.&lt;SEP&gt;A model refers to a trained neural network used for classification tasks.&lt;SEP&gt;A model in the context of neural networks refers to an architecture that performs classification tasks, such as GoogLeNet and Clarifai submissions discussed in the text.&lt;SEP&gt;The model employs very deep convolutional features to achieve high performance without task-specific heuristics.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-414840d58c9c17244c8e4774f512dc8f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ee7c860b03e66807d924aa12f0a62399&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6247855fe0930ba59c41d64d91122ec1&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-45b8e81b5253dda8099181146e449c4b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-57f210dde350132bd52b55e78346cd16&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-13cc89ee2c4ad3ccacc469ae7d4c8d43&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-978a7e2e478746fb8097d20c2ae24e6a</data>
      <data key="d4">Very_Deep_Convolutional_Networks_for_Large-Scale_Image_Recognition_content_list.json</data>
      <data key="d5">1774858959</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Image Content">
      <data key="d0">Image Content</data>
      <data key="d1">content</data>
      <data key="d2">The visual information within sampled image crops used for training.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-414840d58c9c17244c8e4774f512dc8f</data>
      <data key="d4">Very_Deep_Convolutional_Networks_for_Large-Scale_Image_Recognition_content_list.json</data>
      <data key="d5">1774858959</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Pre-trained Weights">
      <data key="d0">Pre-trained Weights</data>
      <data key="d1">data</data>
      <data key="d2">Initial neural network weights obtained from training at scale $S=256$, used for initializing subsequent training.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-414840d58c9c17244c8e4774f512dc8f</data>
      <data key="d4">Very_Deep_Convolutional_Networks_for_Large-Scale_Image_Recognition_content_list.json</data>
      <data key="d5">1774858959</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Learning Rate">
      <data key="d0">Learning Rate</data>
      <data key="d1">method</data>
      <data key="d2">A parameter in training that specifies the step size for updating neural network weights, adjusted here to $10^{-3}$ during the transition to $S = 384$.&lt;SEP&gt;The learning rate is a hyperparameter controlling the step size during gradient descent, initially set to 0.01.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-414840d58c9c17244c8e4774f512dc8f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-70df778c9b358a55553c2b4f57adb424</data>
      <data key="d4">Very_Deep_Convolutional_Networks_for_Large-Scale_Image_Recognition_content_list.json</data>
      <data key="d5">1774858959</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Neural Network">
      <data key="d0">Neural Network</data>
      <data key="d1">content</data>
      <data key="d2">A neural network is a computational model used in deep learning, consisting of layers of interconnected weights.&lt;SEP&gt;A neural network with 22 weight layers utilizing various convolution filters such as 1x1, 3x3, and 5x5, with a topology that reduces spatial resolution in early layers for efficient computation.&lt;SEP&gt;A computational model used for machine learning tasks, especially in deep learning and computer vision, that can be trained using various scales and techniques.&lt;SEP&gt;Neural networks are computational models inspired by biological neural systems, used for machine learning tasks including pattern recognition and classification.&lt;SEP&gt;Neural networks are computational models evaluated using testing protocols to assess performance.&lt;SEP&gt;A neural network model employed for image localization tasks using convolutional layers and regression methods.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-414840d58c9c17244c8e4774f512dc8f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ec1e400414ae226381210995dc5442d4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-235bdad3a44d342f2586c7f9c0c1d5f2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d6f4d23968c5e45cadd7773c219289a0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6d33ecd72d8316d1931ae7b8ae81c712&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-423fe6d6525f200bb97fe2234b6ad1a9</data>
      <data key="d4">Very_Deep_Convolutional_Networks_for_Large-Scale_Image_Recognition_content_list.json</data>
      <data key="d5">1774858959</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Training Techniques">
      <data key="d0">Training Techniques</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Methods such as fixing the scale $S$ or transitioning between scales to optimize neural network training.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-414840d58c9c17244c8e4774f512dc8f</data>
      <data key="d4">Very_Deep_Convolutional_Networks_for_Large-Scale_Image_Recognition_content_list.json</data>
      <data key="d5">1774858960</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Training Efficiency">
      <data key="d0">Training Efficiency</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">The goal of improving the speed and effectiveness of neural network training through methods like pre-training and learning rate adjustments.</data>
