      <data key="d1">content</data>
      <data key="d2">Train refers to the process of teaching neural networks by feeding data, typically involving configuration and preprocessing steps.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-0ab6dde5b80886f30a7bb92c12b0d072</data>
      <data key="d4">Very_Deep_Convolutional_Networks_for_Large-Scale_Image_Recognition_content_list.json</data>
      <data key="d5">1774859014</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Mean RGB Value">
      <data key="d0">Mean RGB Value</data>
      <data key="d1">content</data>
      <data key="d2">The mean RGB value is an average color computed over the training set used for preprocessing images by subtracting it from each pixel.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-0ab6dde5b80886f30a7bb92c12b0d072</data>
      <data key="d4">Very_Deep_Convolutional_Networks_for_Large-Scale_Image_Recognition_content_list.json</data>
      <data key="d5">1774859015</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Spatial Padding">
      <data key="d0">Spatial Padding</data>
      <data key="d1">content</data>
      <data key="d2">Spatial padding involves adding extra pixels (e.g., 1 pixel for 3×3 filters) around input to preserve resolution after convolution.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-0ab6dde5b80886f30a7bb92c12b0d072</data>
      <data key="d4">Very_Deep_Convolutional_Networks_for_Large-Scale_Image_Recognition_content_list.json</data>
      <data key="d5">1774859015</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Filter">
      <data key="d0">Filter</data>
      <data key="d1">content</data>
      <data key="d2">Filters are matrices applied in convolutional layers to detect features; examples include 3×3 and 1×1 filters.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-0ab6dde5b80886f30a7bb92c12b0d072</data>
      <data key="d4">Very_Deep_Convolutional_Networks_for_Large-Scale_Image_Recognition_content_list.json</data>
      <data key="d5">1774859015</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Max-Pooling">
      <data key="d0">Max-Pooling</data>
      <data key="d1">content</data>
      <data key="d2">Max-pooling is a pooling operation that selects the maximum value within a specified window (e.g., 2×2) to downsample feature maps.&lt;SEP&gt;Max-pooling is a technique to combine features by selecting the maximum value across scales.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-0ab6dde5b80886f30a7bb92c12b0d072&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-910b19d5d7e003782ec85519b01d0c2b</data>
      <data key="d4">Very_Deep_Convolutional_Networks_for_Large-Scale_Image_Recognition_content_list.json</data>
      <data key="d5">1774859015</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Batch Size">
      <data key="d0">Batch Size</data>
      <data key="d1">content</data>
      <data key="d2">The batch size specifies the number of images processed simultaneously during training; not explicitly mentioned but implied in training procedures.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-0ab6dde5b80886f30a7bb92c12b0d072</data>
      <data key="d4">Very_Deep_Convolutional_Networks_for_Large-Scale_Image_Recognition_content_list.json</data>
      <data key="d5">1774859015</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge">
      <data key="d0">ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge</data>
      <data key="d1">event</data>
      <data key="d2">The ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge (ILSVRC) is a competitive event focused on evaluating the performance of image recognition systems.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-185820c0acd5f2e9b1560edd052c7535</data>
      <data key="d4">Very_Deep_Convolutional_Networks_for_Large-Scale_Image_Recognition_content_list.json</data>
      <data key="d5">1774859015</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Ground-Truth Category">
      <data key="d0">Ground-Truth Category</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">The ground-truth category refers to the actual class label assigned to an image, used as a reference in evaluation criteria.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-185820c0acd5f2e9b1560edd052c7535</data>
      <data key="d4">Very_Deep_Convolutional_Networks_for_Large-Scale_Image_Recognition_content_list.json</data>
      <data key="d5">1774859015</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Top-5 Predicted Categories">
      <data key="d0">Top-5 Predicted Categories</data>
      <data key="d1">data</data>
      <data key="d2">The top-5 predicted categories are the five most probable classes projected by an image recognition model for a given image.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-185820c0acd5f2e9b1560edd052c7535</data>
      <data key="d4">Very_Deep_Convolutional_Networks_for_Large-Scale_Image_Recognition_content_list.json</data>
      <data key="d5">1774859015</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Evaluation Criterion">
      <data key="d0">Evaluation Criterion</data>
      <data key="d1">method</data>
      <data key="d2">The evaluation criterion is a method used to assess the accuracy of image recognition models, specifically measuring the proportion of instances where the true category falls outside the top-5 predictions.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-185820c0acd5f2e9b1560edd052c7535</data>
      <data key="d4">Very_Deep_Convolutional_Networks_for_Large-Scale_Image_Recognition_content_list.json</data>
      <data key="d5">1774859015</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Classification Performance">
      <data key="d0">Classification Performance</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">The classification performance refers to the effectiveness of image recognition models in correctly identifying categories, as measured by specific evaluation criteria.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-185820c0acd5f2e9b1560edd052c7535</data>
      <data key="d4">Very_Deep_Convolutional_Networks_for_Large-Scale_Image_Recognition_content_list.json</data>
      <data key="d5">1774859015</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Network A">
      <data key="d0">Network A</data>
      <data key="d1">content</data>
      <data key="d2">Network A is a convolutional neural network with 11 weight layers, including 8 convolutional and 3 fully connected layers.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-f8bca6a740a08f56dc0559932aebab28</data>
      <data key="d4">Very_Deep_Convolutional_Networks_for_Large-Scale_Image_Recognition_content_list.json</data>
      <data key="d5">1774859016</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Network E">
      <data key="d0">Network E</data>
      <data key="d1">content</data>
      <data key="d2">Network E is a convolutional neural network with 19 weight layers, comprising 16 convolutional and 3 fully connected layers.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-f8bca6a740a08f56dc0559932aebab28</data>
      <data key="d4">Very_Deep_Convolutional_Networks_for_Large-Scale_Image_Recognition_content_list.json</data>
      <data key="d5">1774859016</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Channel Width">
      <data key="d0">Channel Width</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Channel width refers to the number of channels in convolutional layers, which starts at 64 and increases by a factor of 2 after each max-pooling layer, reaching 512.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-f8bca6a740a08f56dc0559932aebab28</data>
      <data key="d4">Very_Deep_Convolutional_Networks_for_Large-Scale_Image_Recognition_content_list.json</data>
      <data key="d5">1774859016</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Action Classification">
      <data key="d0">Action Classification</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Action classification involves predicting the action performed in images, based on image representations and bounding boxes.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-10bad65f675245d138aefe0373476c36</data>
      <data key="d4">Very_Deep_Convolutional_Networks_for_Large-Scale_Image_Recognition_content_list.json</data>
